image.title: Marble Temple
image.caption: Buddhist monks present alms bowls at Wat Benchamabophit, also known as the Marble Temple, in Bangkok, Thailand. The iconic temple is pictured on the back of the five-baht coin in Thai currency.
image.credit: Photograph by Steven Raymer, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Buddhist monks in orange robes lining up outside the Marble Temple in Bangkok to present alms bowls

social.og:title: Marble Temple | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Buddhist monks line up outside Wat Benchamabophit, also known as the Marble Temple, in Bangkok, Thailand, to present alms bowls in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: In Transit
image.caption: Travelers await trains at the Trans-Siberian Railroad Station in Novosibirsk, Russia. Novosibirsk is the third largest city in Russia, mainly because of its place on the Ob River and its role as a transportation and commerce hub.
image.credit: Photograph by Dean Conger, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Travelers waiting at a train station in Novosibirsk, Russia

social.og:title: In Transit | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Travelers in Novosibirsk, Russia, wait for their trains in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Ice Science
image.caption: Scientists study Antarctica's winter ice for life-forms in this photo from the May 1996 issue. Certain organisms such as algae and mites are only found on the frozen continent, so every expedition provides valuable information.
image.credit: Photograph by Maria Stenzel, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Scientists in cold-weather gear on a swing suspended over ice forms in Antarctica

social.og:title: Ice Science | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Scientists are suspended over ice forms to look for signs of life in Antarctica in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Armistice Day
image.caption: President Franklin Delano Roosevelt leads a ceremony at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier on Armistice Day in 1936. The tomb, located in Arlington National Cemetery, honors members of the military who have died but cannot be identified.
image.credit: Photograph by J. Baylor Roberts, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: President Franklin Delano Roosevelt leading a memorial ceremony at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier

social.og:title: Armistice Day | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: President Franklin Delano Roosevelt leads a ceremony at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier on Armistice Day in 1936 in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Taxi Driver
image.caption: Idling at a market, a Uygur motorcycle taxi driver waits for his next fare in Kashgar, Xinjiang Province, China. Job opportunities for the Muslim minority people group in western China are scarce.
image.credit: Photograph by Carolyn Drake, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: A man on a motorcycle taxi waiting for his next fare at a market in Kashgar, China

social.og:title: Taxi Driver | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A Uygur motorcycle taxi driver awaits his next fare at a market in Kashgar, China, in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Following the Scent
image.caption: Canine athletes follow scented bait in a hound trailing event in England's Lake District. The sport is similar to fox hunting, without the live prey. Dogs can hit 30 miles an hour during the race.
image.credit: Photograph by Annie Griffiths, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Hound dogs jumping over a stone fence during a hound trailing event

social.og:title: Following the Scent | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Canine athletes chase a scent in a hound trailing event in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Teachers in Training
image.caption: Spellbound students compound nitrobenzene at Kenya Science Teachers College in the 1960s. The school is now known as the Kenya Science Campus, as part of the University of Nairobi, and offers a bachelor's degree in science education.
image.credit: Photograph by Bruce Dale, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Two college students staring at a glass pipette full of liquid

social.og:title: Teachers in Training | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Students at the Kenya Science Teachers College in the 1960s compound nitrobenzene in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Lending Library
image.caption: In this photo from the April 1947 issue, people in Hong Kong have become engrossed in stories they just borrowed from a sidewalk lending library. The original caption states that one could buy 13 stories for one cent.
image.credit: Photograph by Three Lions Inc, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: People sitting on a sidewalk reading with a wall of illustrated stories behind them

social.og:title: Lending Library | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Enthralled readers sit on the sidewalk in front of a lending library in Hong Kong in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Sunset Meditations
image.caption: Village elders meditate on the sunset from an outcropping above Debre Sina, Eritrea. A story in the June 1996 issue told of the new country's victory in claiming independence from Ethiopia after 30 years of war.
image.credit: Photograph by Robert Caputo, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Elderly men in Eritrea dressed in white cloths and sitting on a rock outcropping while meditating

social.og:title: Sunset Meditations | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Village elders meditate on the sunset on an outcropping over Debre Sina, Eritrea, in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Blue Barn
image.caption: In Párnica, Slovakia, a woman feeds chickens perched in the window of a barn.
image.credit: Photograph by John Eastcott and Yva Momatiuk, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: A woman in a head scarf feeds chickens perched in a window of a blue barn in Slovakia

social.og:title: Blue Barn | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A woman in Slovakia feeds chickens perching on the window of a barn in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Starry Night
image.caption: A long exposure shows the movement of stars over Llullaillaco, Andes Mountains, Chile. The peak of this dormant volcano is more than 22,000 feet high and last erupted in 1877.
image.credit: Photograph by Maria Stenzel, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Star trails over a dormant volcano in the Andes Mountains

social.og:title: Starry Night | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: A long exposure shows the movement of stars over Llullaillaco, a dormant volcano in the Andes Mountains, in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Presidential Address
image.caption: In the U.S. Capitol Rotunda, President Lyndon B. Johnson delivers remarks at the signing of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. The VRA, which ensured protections for voters of all races, was gutted by a 2013 U.S.Supreme Court ruling that claimed a key section of the legislation was no longer relevant.
image.credit: Photograph by Joe Scherschel, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: President Lyndon B. Johnson speaking in front of a crowd inside the U.S. Capitol Rotunda

social.og:title: Presidential Address | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: President Lyndon B. Johnson announces victory for the 1965 Voting Rights Act in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Sorting Mail
image.caption: A story in the July 1954 issue sang the praises of the United States Postal Service, calling it "everyone's servant." Here, workers at a post office in New York sort through airmail letters.
image.credit: Photograph by Volkmar Wentzel, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: Postal workers sorting mail at a facility in New York in the 1950s

social.og:title: Sorting Mail | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Postal workers sort airmail at a facility in New York in the 1950s in this image from our photography archives.

image.title: Baby Panda
image.caption: Tai Shan, whose name means Peaceful Mountain, was the first giant panda born at the Smithsonian's National Zoo in Washington, D.C., to survive infancy. Now 15 years old, Tai Shan lives at the China Conservation and Research Center for the Giant Panda.
image.credit: Photograph by Michael Nichols, Nat Geo Image Collection
image.alt_text: A year-old panda cub in an indoor inclosure at Smithsonian's National Zoo in Washington, DC

social.og:title: Baby Panda | Nat Geo Photo of the Day
social.og:description: Tai Shan, the first giant panda to survive infancy at Smithsonian's National Zoo in Washington, D.C., seemingly waves to his fans in this image from our photography archives.
